RabbitMQ is a message broker.

◾ Producers publish messages to exchanges.
◾ Exchanges route messages to queues using routing rules.
◾ Messages are pushed to consumers.
◾ Once acknowledged, messages are deleted.




 What Kafka Really Is

Kafka is a distributed event log.

◾ Producers append events to partitions.
◾ Messages remain based on retention policy, not consumption.
◾ Consumers pull messages and track progress using offsets.
◾ Events can be rewound, replayed, and reprocessed.

Built for high-throughput event streaming where many consumers read the same data independently.


Tool	Best for
RabbitMQ-	Task queues, async jobs, request–reply
Redis Streams-	Lightweight streaming, fast processing
Apache Kafka-	Event streaming, analytics, high scale
